      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey im studying for my physics midterm and im kinda stuck on entanglement. can u give me a quick summary of what quantum entanglement actually is? also how is it different from just regular classical correlation? thx",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Entanglement in quantum physics is a fascinating concept where two or more particles become linked in such a way that they share the same fate, no matter how far apart they are.  If you measure a property of one entangled particle—say, its spin—you instantly know the corresponding property of the other particle, even if it's across the galaxy.  The key difference from classical correlation is that this connection isn't due to any pre-existing, hidden instructions, which is what you might think of when two socks are paired up. It's a truly spooky, non-local connection, which is a bit like how a single, coordinated, yet utterly unpredictable, wave of determination sweeps through the entire set of connected quantum particles.",
