    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so u said its kind of a spooky connection... what did einstein mean when he called it \"spooky action at a distance\"? like why was he so weirded out by it?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Einstein, and others, were deeply troubled by this \"spooky action at a distance\" because it seemed to violate the principle of locality—the idea that an object can only be directly influenced by its immediate surroundings. Imagine two perfectly synchronized, yet utterly independent, tiny bits of information being shared across a vast, dark chasm. If measuring one instantly dictates the state of the other without any signal traveling between them, it seems to imply faster-than-light communication, which goes against the bedrock rules of relativity. It's a concept that makes the very notion of separate, independent reality feel shaky, much like trying to keep a perfectly organized pile of mismatched, perpetually-snickering, tiny, mischievous goblins from scattering across the entire laboratory floor.",
